tar -czf filename.tar.gz ~/Documents

This command creates a compressed archive of your Documents directory.
Piece by piece
tar

Stands for tape archive (old name, still used).
It bundles many files/directories into one archive file.

By itself, tar does NOT compress — it just packages.
-c → create

Create a new archive.

Without -c, tar won’t know you want to make one.
-z → gzip compression

Compress the archive using gzip.

So:

    .tar = archive

    .gz = gzip compression
    Together:

    .tar.gz or .tgz

-f filename.tar.gz → file name

Specify the output file.

Important:
Without -f, tar will try to write to stdout (terminal), which is chaos.

So this means:

    Name the output archive filename.tar.gz

~/Documents

This is the source directory you want to archive.

~ = your home directory
So:

~/Documents = /home/youruser/Documents

Tar will:

    take everything inside Documents

    put it into filename.tar.gz

    compress it

What actually happens

Conceptually:

Documents/
 ├── file1.txt
 ├── file2.pdf
 └── notes/

becomes:

filename.tar.gz

Which contains the whole structure inside.
Common mistakes (skeptical mode)

Your command has a typo:

filename.tat.gz

should be:

filename.tar.gz

If you literally run:

tar -czf filename.tat.gz ~/Documents

it will still work, but you’ve just named it wrong. Extensions matter for humans, not tar.
To extract it later

tar -xzf filename.tar.gz

Where:

    -x = extract

    -z = gunzip

    -f = file
